# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bird-conservation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] US$5 billion in funding for a project called the "Protecting Our Planet Challenge" was announced for the initiative in September 2021.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] In December 2022, 30 by 30 was agreed at the COP15 meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and became a target of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] This includes the G7 and European Union.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] The initiative has attracted controversy over indigenous rights issues.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] As of May 2026, 17.3% of terrestrial land and inland waters and 9.8% of marine areas are protected.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Including OECM's (Other Effective Area-based Conservation Measures) the percent of protected areas are 18.4% of terrestrial and inland waters and 10.0% of marine areas.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] The European Commission's Biodiversity strategy for 2030 was proposed on May 20, 2020, as the European Union's contribution to a post-2020 global biodiversity framework.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] The plan includes turning 30% of EU territory to protected area by 2030 and 10% to strictly protected area.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] However as of 2023 EU is not on track to meet the targets.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] The biodiversity strategy is a core part of the European Green Deal, and also intended to support green recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] In July 2023 after many debates the European parliament adopted a version of the Nature restoration law, aiming to restore nature on 20% of the territory of the European Union by 2030.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] In 2024, the European Union passed a nature restoration law aiming to restore 20% of degraded ecosystems by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] On January 27, 2021, President Joe Biden issued an executive order on "Tackling the Climate Crisis at Home and Abroad".
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Participating federal agencies included the U.S.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Department of Commerce, and Council on Environmental Quality.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] The order also established a California Biodiversity Collaborative composed of representatives of government agencies, Native tribes, experts, and other stakeholders.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] The official report, *Pathways to 30x30 California*, was issued by the California Natural Resources Agency on 22 April 2022.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has progressed unevenly, and researchers caution that simply increasing the extent of protected areas is not sufficient to halt biodiversity loss.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Some conservationists argue that the 30% figure lacks a clear scientific justification and risks being treated as a symbolic or political benchmark rather than a threshold grounded in ecological evidence.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] At the same time, other researchers and advocacy groups contend that 30% may in fact be too low to secure long‑term ecological integrity, and point to proposals such as the "Half‑Earth" concept, which calls for roughly 50% of terrestrial and marine realms to be conserved in some form.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] A further concern relates to the quality and effectiveness of protection once areas are designated.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Researchers and NGOs have highlighted the persistence of so‑called "paper parks": protected areas that exist in law but lack adequate funding, staffing or enforcement, allowing activities such as poaching, illegal logging, or unregulated development to continue.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Modelling work by Kuempel et al. suggests that, for exploited species, improving enforcement and management within existing protected areas can in many cases deliver greater conservation benefits than simply expanding the network’s total area without a corresponding increase in resources.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Taken together, this literature underlines that meeting percentage‑based targets without adequate governance capacity risks diluting scarce conservation resources.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Other research has examined conditions under which expanding protected areas can still be beneficial even when management budgets do not increase.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Their results suggest that, in landscapes where human pressures are spatially clumped near reserve boundaries, strategically increasing the size of protected areas can create more secure habitat refuges even without proportional increases in staffing or enforcement.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] In practice, the 30 by 30 commitment has also prompted debate over how "protected" or "conserved" areas are defined for monitoring and reporting purposes.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has also raised concerns about “green grabbing” and green colonialism in the way new protected and conserved areas may be established.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Similar critiques have been echoed by human rights organisations and researchers who argue that percentage-based conservation targets can replicate earlier "fortress conservation" models if they are implemented through top-down land designations that disregard customary tenure and existing uses.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] More broadly, some Indigenous organisations have criticised the way 30 by 30 has been promoted and negotiated, arguing that it risks appropriating Indigenous lands under the guise of biodiversity conservation.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] The COP15 included 196 parties in negotiations, with competing views regarding the adoption of the 30 by 30 target being wide-spread and well documented.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] The resulting agreement of the conference, the Convention on Biological Diversity, was signed by every party, with the exception of two: the United States and the Vatican.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Towards the end of the talks, a negotiator from Democratic Republic of the Congo raised objections to the agreement, citing a lack of funding separate from the current Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] After a delay, COP15 president and Chinese environment minister Huang Runqiu overruled the objection due to a legal technicality, resulting in the passage of the agreement.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] Delegates from the DRC, Cameroon, and Uganda were reportedly displeased with the outcome.
[src:bird-conservation/30-by-30] After the agreement was passed, the DRC's government announced that it would not recognize it as valid.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The book was effectively the first "field guide" for non-specialists.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick provides an accurate illustration of each species, from life if possible, or from skins.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The common and scientific name(s) are listed, citing the naming authorities.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The bird is described, with its distribution and behaviour, often with extensive quotations from printed sources or correspondents.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Those who provided skins or information are acknowledged.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The species are grouped into families such as "Of the Falcon", using the limited and conflicting scientific sources of the time.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The families of land birds are further grouped into birds of prey, omnivorous birds, insectivorous birds, and granivorous birds, while the families of water birds are simply listed, with related families side by side.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Each species entry begins on a new page; any spaces at the ends of entries are filled with tail-pieces, small, often humorous woodcuts of country life.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] *British Birds* remains in print, and has attracted the attention of authors such as Jenny Uglow.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Critics note Bewick's skill as a naturalist as well as an engraver.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The arrangement of the species was by alphabetical order in Gessner's *Historia animalium*, and by arbitrary criteria in most other early works.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The first modern ornithology, intended to describe all the then-known birds worldwide, was produced by Ray and Willughby and published in Latin as *Ornithologiae Libri Tres* (*Three Books of Ornithology*) in 1676, and in English, as *The Ornithology of Francis Willughby of Middleton*, in 1678.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Its innovative features were an effective classification system based on anatomical features, including the bird's beak, feet and overall size, and a dichotomous key, which helped readers to identify birds by guiding them to the page describing that group.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The authors also placed an asterisk against species of which they had no first-hand knowledge, and were therefore unable to verify.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The commercial success of the *Ornithology* is unknown, but it was historically significant, influencing writers including René Réaumur, Mathurin Jacques Brisson, Georges Cuvier and Carl Linnaeus in compiling their own works.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] George Edwards was a leading British naturalist and illustrator in the 17th century.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] He was the librarian to the Royal College of Physicians with access to their collection of 8,000 books, and he used these, together with stuffed and live animals, to produce illustrated publications.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] His four-volume *A Natural History of Uncommon Birds* (1743–1751) and its three supplements covered more than 600 natural history topics, and his publications enabled Linnaeus to name 350 bird species, including many type specimens.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] When he was researching published sources for his bird project, Bewick relied particularly on Edwards' book and the multi-volume *Histoire Naturelle* of the French naturalist Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Thomas Bewick was born at Cherryburn, a house in the parish of Mickley, Northumberland, and he was apprenticed at the age of 14 to Ralph Beilby, an engraver in Newcastle upon Tyne, and learnt how to engrave on wood and metal.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The business prospered, becoming Newcastle's leading engraving service with an enviable reputation for high-quality work and good service.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Now partners, Bielby and Bewick published their *History of Quadrupeds* in 1790, and its success encouraged them to consider producing a new book on British birds.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] In preparation for this major work, Bewick spent several years engraving the necessary wood blocks.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick became well known for his engravings, including the woodcuts for Oliver Goldsmith's *Traveller* and *The Deserted Village*, for Thomas Parnell's *Hermit*, and for William Somervile's *Chase*.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Perhaps the best known of his prints is *The Chillingham Bull*, executed on an exceptionally large woodblock for Marmaduke Tunstall, a Yorkshire landowner.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick also produced and illustrated several editions of Aesop's Fables throughout his creative life.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] His success meant that Bewick had at least 30 pupils who worked for him and Beilby as apprentices, the first of whom was his younger brother John.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick died at his home on 8 November 1828.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] He was buried in Ovingham churchyard, beside his late wife Isabella, who had died two years earlier on 1 February 1826, and not far from his parents and his brother John.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The preface to *A History of British Birds* states that "while one of the editors [Bewick] of this work was engaged in preparing the cuts, which are faithfully drawn from Nature, and engraved upon wood, the compilation of the descriptions ..
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] What the preface does not say is the reason for this statement about the "editors", which was an angry stand-off between Bewick and Beilby.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Beilby's original intention was to have an introduction which merely thanked Bewick for his "assistance", and a title-page naming Beilby as the sole author.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's friend (and his wife's godfather) Thomas Hornby heard of this, and informed Bewick.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] An informal trade panel met to judge the matter, and the preface as printed was the result; Beilby's name did not appear on the title-page.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Each species of bird is presented in a few pages (generally between two and four; occasionally, as with the mallard or "Common Wild Duck", a few more).
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The first item is a woodcut print of the bird, always either perched or standing on the ground, even in the case of water birds – such as the smew – that (as winter visitors) do not nest in Britain, and consequently are rarely seen away from water there.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then presents the name, with variations, and the Latin and French equivalents.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] For example, "The Musk Duck" is also named on the line below as "Cairo, Guinea, or Indian Duck", and the next line "(*Anas moschata*, Linn.—*Le Canard Musque*, Buff.)" provides the scholarly references to the giving of the Latin binomial by Linnaeus (Linn) and a French description by Buffon (Buff).
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The text begins by stating the size of the bird.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then describes the bird, typically in one paragraph, naming any notable features such as the colour of the eyes ("irides"), the bill, the legs, and plumage on each part of the body.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Next, the origin and distribution of the species are discussed, with notes or quotations from authorities such as John Ray, Gilbert White and Buffon.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then mentions any other facts of interest about the bird; in the case of the musk duck, this concerns its "musky smell, which arises from the liquor secreted in the glands on the rump".
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] If the bird hybridizes with other species, this is described, along with whether the hybrids are fertile ("productive").
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Finally, Bewick acknowledges anyone who had helped him.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The musk duck is stated to have been drawn from a "living specimen" which was however "excepting the head, entirely white", unlike the "general appearance" shown in the woodcut; the bird "was lent to this work by William Losh, Esq., of Point Pleasant, near Newcastle".
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Losh, one of Bewick's many collaborators, was a wealthy partner in Losh, Wilson and Bell, manufacturers of chemicals and iron.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Many of the birds, especially the rarer species, were necessarily illustrated from skins rather than from life.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] For example, for the Sabine's snipe, "The author was favoured by N.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The grouping of species gave Bewick difficulty, as the scientific sources of the time did not agree on how to arrange the species in families, or on a sequence or grouping of those families.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick, for example, uses family groups like "Of the Falcon", in which he includes buzzards and sparrowhawks as well as what are now called falcons.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Each account is closed with a miniature woodcut known from its position in the text as a tail-piece.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] These small artworks depict aspects of country life, often with humorous subjects, but all with Bewick's eye for detail, style, and precision.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Some add to the illustration of the bird in question, as for example the heron, where the tail-piece shows one heron catching an eel, and another flying away.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The tail-piece for Sabine's snipe, a gamebird, shows a hunter firing, and a small bird falling to the ground.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] There is no exclusion of human life from the images: one tail-piece depicts a works complete with smoking chimney beside a river.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The first volume "containing the History and Description of Land Birds" begins with a preface, an introduction, and a list of technical terms illustrated with Bewick's woodcuts.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The birds are divided into granivorous (grain eating) and carnivorous groups, which are explained in some detail.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The speed, senses, flight, migration, pairing behaviour and feeding of birds are then discussed, with observations from Spallanzani and Gilbert White, whose *Natural History and Antiquities of Selborne* was published in 1789.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The second volume "containing the History and Description of Water Birds" begins with its own preface, and its own introduction.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick discusses the question of where many seabirds go to breed, revisits the subject of migration, and concludes with reflections on "an all-wise Providence" as shown in Nature.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The 'foreign birds' are not grouped but just listed directly as species, from Bearded Vulture to Mino.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Fifteen birds are included, with no description, and despite their placement in the table of contents, they appear at the front of the volume as an 'Appendix'.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's *Birds* was an immediate best-seller.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] When *Land Birds* appeared, the whole print sold out by the middle of 1798; 1000 copies of the demy size (8+3⁄4 in × 5+5⁄8 in, 220 mm × 140 mm), 850 of the royal octavo (10 in × 6+1⁄4 in, 250 mm × 160 mm), and 24 of the grand imperial (22 in × 30 in, 560 mm × 760 mm).
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The 1829 *Magazine of Natural History* commented that "Montagu's *Ornithological Dictionary* and Bewick's *Birds* .. have rendered [the] department of natural history popular throughout the land".
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The Tate Gallery writes that Bewick's " best illustrations ... are in his natural history books.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Dissenting from the general tone of praise for Bewick, Jacob Kainen cites claims that "many of the best tailpieces in the *History of British birds* were drawn by Robert Johnson", and that "the greater number of those contained in the second volume were engraved by Clennell.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] To Bewick, nature was the source of joy, challenge and perpetual consolation.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Hilary Spurling, reviewing Uglow's biography of Bewick in *The Observer*, writes that when *Birds* appeared, people all over Britain "became his pupils".
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Spurling cites Charles Kingsley's story of his father's hunting friends from the New Forest mocking him for buying "a book 'about dicky-birds", until, astonished, they saw the book and discovered "things they had known all their lives and never even noticed".
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The *History* is repeatedly mentioned in Charlotte Brontë's 1847 novel *Jane Eyre*.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] John Reed throws the *History of British Birds* at Jane when she is ten; Jane uses the book as a place to which to escape, away from the painful Reed household; and Jane also bases her artwork on Bewick's illustrations.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Jane and Mr Rochester use bird names for each other, including linnet, dove, skylark, eagle, and falcon.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Peter Hall's 1974 film *Akenfield* (from the 1969 book by Ronald Blythe) contains a scene where the grandfather as a young man is reaping a cornfield.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] He weeps when he accidentally crushes a bird's egg, an image derived from Bewick's tail-piece woodcut for the partridge.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The woodcut shows a reaper with a scythe, a dead bird and its nest of a dozen eggs on the ground under the scythe, which has just lifted.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] George Ewart Evans used the image on the title-page of his 1956 book about Blaxhall (near Charsfield, on which 'Akenfield' is probably partly based).
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's reputation as a wood engraver was at its height in the nineteenth century, with the critic John Ruskin writing that the way Bewick had engraved the feathers of his birds was "the most masterly thing ever done in woodcutting".
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The advent of mechanical printing techniques from the 1860s led to something of a decline in his importance, but his fame, already nationwide across Britain for his *Birds*, grew during the nineteenth century.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] In 1830, William Yarrell named Bewick's swan in his honour, and Bewick's son Robert engraved the bird for later editions of *British Birds*.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick had met the American naturalist and bird painter John James Audubon in 1827, and had given him a copy of his *Quadrupeds* for his children.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The American returned the compliment by naming a newly-discovered US bird species as Bewick's wren in honour of his friend.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The way in which Bewick had organised the text and illustrations in his *Birds* takes the form of, and sets a precedent for, modern field guides.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Indeed, the French naturalist François Holandre (1753–1830) assembled a field guide using Bewick's woodcuts as early as 1800.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] A selection of tail-pieces from the book, where they have no captions.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Volume 1 first appeared in 1797, and was reprinted several times in 1797, then again in 1798 and 1800.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Volume 2 first appeared in 1804 (price 11.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] The first imprint was "Newcastle : Printed by Sol.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Hodgson, for Beilby & Bewick; London: Sold by them, and G.C. and J.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] In 1821 a new edition appeared with supplements to both volumes and additional figures, with the imprint "Printed by Edward Walker, Pilgrim-Street, for T.
[src:bird-conservation/a-history-of-british-birds] Charnley, Newcastle; and Longman and co., London, 1821." The book was reprinted in many subsequent versions with a 6th edition in 1826, another in 1832, an 8th edition in 1847, and a royal octavo 'Memorial Edition' in 1885.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] The **Accipitriformes** (/ækˌsɪpɪtrɪˈfɔːrmiːz/; from Latin **accipiter** 'hawk' and **formes** 'having the form of') are an order of birds that includes most of the diurnal birds of prey, including hawks, eagles, vultures, kites, ospreys and secretary birds, but not falcons or seriemas.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] The generally nocturnal owls, also considered birds of prey, are a separate order from the accipitriformes.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] For a long time, the majority view was to include them with the falcons in the Falconiformes, but many authorities now recognize a separate order Accipitriformes.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] A DNA study published in 2008 indicated that falcons are not closely related to the Accipitriformes, being instead more closely related to parrots and passerines.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] The British Ornithologists' Union already recognized the Accipitriformes, and has adopted the move of Falconiformes.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] The DNA-based proposal and the NACC and IOC classifications include the New World vultures in the Accipitriformes, while the SACC classifies the New World vultures as a separate order, the Cathartiformes.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] When Cathartiformes is considered a separate order, sister to Accipitriformes, Accipitriformes sensu lato is called Accipitrimorphae.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] The Accipitriformes are known from the Middle Eocene and typically have a sharply hooked beak with a soft cere housing the nostrils.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] Their wings are long and fairly broad, suitable for soaring flight, with the outer four to six primary feathers emarginated.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] They have strong legs and feet with raptorial claws and opposable hind claws.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] Almost all Accipitriformes are carnivorous, hunting by sight during the day or at twilight.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] They are exceptionally long-lived, and most have low reproductive rates.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] The young have a long, very fast-growing fledgling stage, followed by 3–8 weeks of nest care after first flight, and 1 to 3 years as sexually immature adults.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] The sexes have conspicuously different sizes and sometimes a female is more than twice as heavy as her mate.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] This sexual dimorphism is sometimes most extreme in specialized bird-eaters, such as the *Accipiter* hawks.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] Monogamy is the general rule, although an alternative mate is often selected if one dies.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] Accipitriformes, currently with 262 species and 75 genera in 4 extant families and possibly 1 extinct family, is the largest diurnal raptor order.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] DNA sequence analyses suggest that divergences within Accipitriformes began around the Eocene/Oligocene boundary about 34 mya, with the split of the group including genera *Elanus* and *Gampsonyx* from the other Accipitriformes genera.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] For a complete list of species, see list of Accipitriformes species.
[src:bird-conservation/accipitriformes] Phylogeny of Accipitriformes sensu stricto based on Nagy, J. & Tökölyi, J.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] The wings are short, with 10 primaries and about 11 secondaries; the tail long and rounded.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] The genus *Aegotheles* was introduced in 1827 by the naturalists Nicholas Vigors and Thomas Horsfield to accommodate a single species, *Caprimulgus novaehollandiae* Latham, 1790.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] This binomial name is considered to be a junior synonym of *Caprimulgus cristatus*, the Australian owlet-nightjar that was introduced by George Shaw earlier in 1790.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] The genus name means "nightjar" or "goatsucker" from Ancient Greek αιξ/*aix*, αιγος/*aigos* meaning "goat" and θηλαζω/*thēlazō* meaning "to suckle".
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] The family Aegothelidae was introduced (as subfamily Aegothelinae within the family Caprimulgidae) in 1853 by the French naturalist Charles Lucien Bonaparte.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] A comprehensive 2003 study analyzing mtDNA sequences of Cytochrome b and ATPase subunit 8 suggests that 12 living species of owlet-nightjar should be recognized, as well as another that became extinct early in the second millennium AD.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] It appears though that they are not as closely related to either as previously thought, and that the owlet-nightjars share a more recent common ancestor with the Apodiformes.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] As has been suggested on occasion since morphological studies of the cranium in the 1960s, they are thus considered a distinct order, **Aegotheliformes**.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] This, the caprimulgiform lineage(s), and the Apodiformes, are postulated to form a clade called Cypselomorphae, with the owlet-nightjars and the Apodiformes forming the clade Daedalornithes.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] In form and habits, however, they are very similar to both caprimulgiform group – or, at first glance, to small owls with huge eyes.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] Owlet-nightjars are an exclusively Australasian group, but close relatives apparently thrived all over Eurasia in the late Paleogene.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] Molecular phylogenetic studies have shown the Aegotheliformes are sister to the Apodiformes containing the hummingbirds, swifts and treeswifts.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] The two orders shared a common ancestor around 57 million years ago.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] The following cladogram is based on a 2003 molecular phylogenetic study that sampled three regions of mitochondrial DNA mainly extracted from museum specimens.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] Some of the nodes were not well supported by the data.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] A fossil proximal right tarsometatarsus (MNZ S42800) was found at the Bannockburn Formation of the Manuherikia Group near the Manuherikia River in Otago, New Zealand.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] Dating from the Early to Middle Miocene (Altonian, 19–16 million years ago), it seems to represent an owlet-nightjar ancestral to *A. novaezealandiae*.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] In 2022, an additional specimen from the same locality was described by Worthy *et al*. as a new extinct species of *Aegotheles*, *A. zealandivetus*.
[src:bird-conservation/aegotheliformes] The holotype specimen is NMNZ S.52917, a distal right tarsometatarsus.
[src:bird-conservation/aequornithes] Aequornithes, as currently understood, includes the clades Gaviiformes (loons), Sphenisciformes (penguins), Procellariiformes (petrels and albatrosses), Ciconiiformes (storks), Suliformes (gannets and cormorants) and Pelecaniformes (pelicans and herons).
[src:bird-conservation/aequornithes] The monophyly of this grouping is supported by several molecular phylogenetic studies.
[src:bird-conservation/aequornithes] It does not include several unrelated groups of aquatic birds such as flamingos and grebes (Mirandornithes), shorebirds, gulls, and auks (Charadriiformes), or the Anseriformes (waterfowl).
[src:bird-conservation/aequornithes] The group first appeared during the Maastrichtian stage of the Late Cretaceous, with the earliest known member being *Pujatopouli* from the López de Bertodano Formation of Seymour Island, Antarctica.
[src:bird-conservation/aequornithes] Based on a whole-genome analysis of the bird orders, the kagu and sunbittern (Eurypygiformes) and the three species of tropicbirds (Phaethontiformes) together styled as the Eurypygimorphae are the closest sister group of the Aequornithes, in a clade later named Phaethoquornithes.
[src:bird-conservation/aequornithes] The cladogram below is based on Burleigh, J.G. et al.
[src:bird-conservation/aequornithes] (2024) with some names after Sangster, G. & Mayr, G.
[src:bird-conservation/aequornithes] The clade **Feraequornithes** was named by Sangster & Mayr, 2021 to include the **Pelecanimorphae** and **Procellariimorphae** to the exclusion of the loons (**Gaviiformes**).
[src:bird-conservation/aequornithes] They defined this clade in the *PhyloCode* as "the least inclusive clade containing *Pelecanus onocrotalus* and *Procellaria aequinoctialis*".
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means re-establishing forest that have either been cut down or lost due to natural causes, such as fire, storm, etc.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Nowadays, the boundaries between afforestation and reforestation projects can be blurred as it may not be so clear what was there before at what point in time.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] An essential aspect of successful afforestation efforts lies in the careful selection of tree species that are well-suited to the local climate and soil conditions.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] By choosing appropriate species, afforested areas can better withstand the impacts of climate change.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Planting and protecting them would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon which is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's current carbon pool.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] However, there has been debate about whether afforestation is beneficial for the sustainable use of natural resources, with some researchers pointing out that tree planting is not the only way to enhance climate mitigation and CO2 capture.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Non-forest areas, such as grasslands and savannas, also benefit the biosphere and humanity, and they need a different management strategy - they are not supposed to be forests.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation critics argue that ecosystems without trees are not necessarily degraded, and many of them can store carbon as they are; for example, savannas and tundra store carbon underground.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Carbon sequestration estimates in these areas often do not include the total amount of carbon reductions in soils and slowing tree growth over time.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation can also negatively affect biodiversity by increasing fragmentation and edge effects on the habitat outside the planted area.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Australia, Canada, China, India, Israel, United States and Europe have afforestation programs to increase carbon dioxide removal in forests and in some cases to reduce desertification.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The term afforestation means establishing new forest on lands that were not forest before (e.g. abandoned agriculture).
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The same definition in other words states that afforestation is "conversion to forest of land that historically has not contained forests".
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means the "conversion to forest of land that has previously contained forests but that has been converted to some other use".
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Agroforestry (this is essentially an agricultural activity carried out in order to grow harvestable crops such as fruits and nuts).
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Tree plantations (carried out in order to produce wood and wood-pulp products; this can be seen as an alternative to cutting down naturally occurring forests).
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] However, the term *afforestation* can also "imply the intentional conversion of native non-forest ecosystems to exotic tree cover and violate biodiversity safeguards".
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The process of afforestation begins with site selection.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Several environmental factors of the site must be analyzed, including climate, soil, vegetation, and human activity.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] These factors will determine the quality of the site, what species of trees should be planted, and what planting method should be used.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] After the forest site has been assessed, the area must be prepared for planting.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Preparation can involve a variety of mechanical or chemical methods, such as chopping, mounding, bedding, herbicides, and prescribed burning.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Once the site is prepared, planting can take place.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] One method for planting is direct seeding, which involves sowing seeds directly into the forest floor.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Another is seedling planting, which is similar to direct seeding except that seedlings already have an established root system.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation by cutting is an option for tree species that can reproduce asexually, where a piece of a tree stem, branch, root, or leaves can be planted onto the forest floor and sprout successfully.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Sometimes special tools, such as a tree planting bar, are used to make planting of trees easier and faster.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] There are several benefits from afforestation such as carbon sequestration, increasing rainfall, prevention of topsoil erosion (from water and wind), flood and landslide mitigation, barriers against high winds, shelter for wildlife, employment and alternative sources of wood products.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation projects create employment opportunities, particularly in rural areas, thus promoting sustainable livelihoods.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] They can create many jobs in various forest-related activities.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Forests are an important part of the global carbon cycle because trees and plants absorb carbon dioxide through photosynthesis.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Therefore, they play an important role in climate change mitigation.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] By removing the greenhouse gas CO2 from the air, forests function as terrestrial carbon sinks, meaning they store large amounts of carbon in the form of biomass, encompassing roots, stems, branches, and leaves.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] By doing so, forests sequester approximately 25% of human carbon emissions annually, playing a critical role in Earth's climate.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Throughout their lifespan, trees continue to sequester carbon, storing atmospheric CO2 long-term.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Sustainable forest management, afforestation, reforestation are therefore important contributions to climate change mitigation.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] An important consideration in such efforts is that forests can turn from sinks to carbon sources.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In 2019 forests took up a third less carbon than they did in the 1990s, due to higher temperatures, droughts and deforestation.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] National-scale forest inventory data also shows trends from 1999 to 2020 that some forests were already approaching climate thresholds shifting them from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The typical tropical forest may become a carbon source by the 2060s.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Researchers have found that, in terms of environmental services, it is better to avoid deforestation than to allow for deforestation to subsequently reforest, as the latter leads to irreversible effects in terms of biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Furthermore, the probability that legacy carbon will be released from soil is higher in a younger boreal forest.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In particular, boreal forests have been noted to support the growth of Armillaria (honey fungus), which is a root pathogen that breaks down compounds necessary for wood integrity, increasing the likelihood of carbon release.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Global greenhouse gas emissions caused by damage to tropical rainforests may have been substantially underestimated until around 2019.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Additionally, the effects of afforestation and reforestation will be farther in the future than keeping existing forests intact.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] It takes much longer − several decades − for the benefits for global warming to manifest to the same carbon sequestration benefits from mature trees in tropical forests and hence from limiting deforestation.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Therefore, scientists consider "the protection and recovery of carbon-rich and long-lived ecosystems, especially natural forests" to be "the major climate solution".
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The planting of trees on marginal crop and pasture lands helps to incorporate carbon from atmospheric CO 2 into biomass.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] For this carbon sequestration process to succeed the carbon must not return to the atmosphere from biomass burning or rotting when the trees die.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Several species of *Ficus* such as *Ficus wakefieldii* have been observed to sequester atmospheric CO2 as calcium oxalate in the presence of oxalotrophic bacteria and fungi, which catabolize the oxalate, which produces calcium carbonate.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The calcium carbonate is precipitated throughout the tree, which also alkalinizes the surrounding soil.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] These species are current candidates for carbon sequestration in agroforestry.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This Calcium-oxalate fixation process was first observed in the *Iroko* tree, which can sequester up to a ton of calcium carbonate in the soil over its lifespan.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Also Cacti, such as the *Saguaro*, transfer carbon from the biological cycle to the geological cycle by forming the mineral calcium carbonate.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover, although this estimate has been criticized, and the true area that has a net cooling effect on the climate when accounting for biophysical feedbacks like albedo is 20-80% lower.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Planting and protecting these trees would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon if the trees survive future climate stress to reach maturity.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] To put this number into perspective, this is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions (as of 2019) .
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's carbon pool in 2019.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Life expectancy of forests varies throughout the world, influenced by tree species, site conditions, and natural disturbance patterns.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In some forests, carbon may be stored for centuries, while in other forests, carbon is released with frequent stand replacing fires.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Forests that are harvested prior to stand replacing events allow for the retention of carbon in manufactured forest products such as lumber.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] However, only a portion of the carbon removed from logged forests ends up as durable goods and buildings.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The remainder ends up as sawmill by-products such as pulp, paper, and pallets.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] If all new construction globally utilized 90% wood products, largely via adoption of mass timber in low rise construction, this could sequester 700 million net tons of carbon per year.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This is in addition to the elimination of carbon emissions from the displaced construction material such as steel or concrete, which are carbon-intense to produce.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] A meta-analysis found that mixed species plantations would increase carbon storage alongside other benefits of diversifying planted forests.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Although a bamboo forest stores less total carbon than a mature forest of trees, a bamboo plantation sequesters carbon at a much faster rate than a mature forest or a tree plantation.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Therefore, the farming of bamboo timber may have significant carbon sequestration potential.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that: "The total carbon stock in forests decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020".
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In Canada's boreal forests as much as 80% of the total carbon is stored in the soils as dead organic matter.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Impacts on temperature are affected by the location of the forest.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] For example, reforestation in boreal or subarctic regions has less impact on climate.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This is because it substitutes a high-albedo, snow-dominated region with a lower-albedo forest canopy.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] By contrast, tropical reforestation projects lead to a positive change such as the formation of clouds.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] These clouds then reflect the sunlight, lowering temperatures.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Planting trees in tropical climates with wet seasons has another advantage.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In such a setting, trees grow more quickly (fixing more carbon) because they can grow year-round.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Trees in tropical climates have, on average, larger, brighter, and more abundant leaves than non-tropical climates.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] A study of the girth of 70,000 trees across Africa has shown that tropical forests fix more carbon dioxide pollution than previously realized.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The research suggested almost one-fifth of fossil fuel emissions are absorbed by forests across Africa, Amazonia and Asia.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation provides other environmental benefits, including increasing the soil quality and its organic carbon levels, reducing the risk of erosion and desertification.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The planting of trees in urban areas is also able to reduce air pollution via the trees' absorption and filtration of pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone, in addition to CO2.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation protects the biodiversity of plants and animals which allows the sustenance of ecosystems that provide clean air, soil fertilization, etc.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Forests support biodiversity conservation, providing habitats for about 80% of the world's biodiversity and contributing to ecosystem restoration and resilience.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Water management can be improved afforestation, as trees regulate hydrological cycles, reduce soil erosion, and prevent water runoff.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Their capacity to capture and store water helps in mitigating floods and droughts.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Forests act as natural air filters, absorbing pollutants and improving air quality.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Urban forestation projects have been successful in reducing respiratory illnesses and enhancing overall air quality in cities.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Trees provide shade and cooling effects.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] By shading and evaporation, forests can lower local temperatures, offering a more comfortable environment in urban areas and reducing the impact of extreme heat.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Tree-planting campaigns are criticised for sometimes targeting areas where forests would not naturally occur, such as grassland and savanna biomes.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Carbon sequestration forecasts of afforestation programmes often insufficiently consider possible carbon reductions in soils as well as slowing tree growth over time.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation can negatively affect biodiversity through increasing fragmentation and edge effects for the habitat remaining outside the planted area.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] New forest plantations can introduce generalist predators that would otherwise not be found in open habitat into the covered area, which could detrimentally increase predation rates on the native species of the area.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] A study by scientists at the British Trust for Ornithology into the decline of British populations of Eurasian curlew found that afforestation had impacted curlew populations through fragmentation of their naturally open grassland habitats and increases in generalist predators.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Questions have also been raised in the scientific community regarding how global afforestation could affect the surface albedo of Earth.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The canopy cover of mature trees could make the surface albedo darker, which causes more heat to be absorbed, potentially raising the temperature of the planet.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This is particularly relevant in parts of the world with high levels of snow cover, due to the significant difference in albedo between highly reflective white snow and darker forest cover which absorbs more solar radiation.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] One significant criticism of reforestation or afforestation efforts that rely on monocultures of - usually conifer - trees is that, while they may increase tree cover, they fail to provide the diverse and complex habitat needed by most woodland creatures.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Monocultures, often planted for commercial purposes or ease of management, lack the biodiversity of natural forests.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] These single-species forests provide limited food sources, shelter, and nesting sites for a wide range of wildlife, and in purely coniferous forests low levels of light may reach the forest floor reducing habitat and variety of plant life.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Many woodland creatures, such as birds, mammals, and insects, rely on a variety of tree species and plant life for survival, and the uniformity of monocultures does not support these varied ecological needs.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] As a result, such reforestation or afforestation efforts may unintentionally create environments that are unsuitable for the very species they aim to protect, thus undermining broader conservation goals.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The Great Green Wall of Africa is a ~5,000 mile forest being planted across the continent to stop the spread of the Sahara Desert to the south.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In Adelaide, South Australia (a city of 1.3 million as of June 2016), Premier Mike Rann (2002 to 2011) launched an urban forest initiative in 2003 to plant 3 million native trees and shrubs by 2014 on 300 project sites across the metro area.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Thousands of Adelaide citizens participated in community planting days on sites including parks, reserves, transport corridors, schools, water courses and coastline.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Only native trees were planted to ensure genetic integrity.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Rann said the project aimed to beautify and cool the city and make it more livable, improve air and water quality, and reduce Adelaide's greenhouse gas emissions by 600,000 tonnes of CO2 per year.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In 2003, the government of Canada created a four-year project called the Forest 2020 Plantation Development and Assessment Initiative, which involved planting 6000 ha of fast-growing forests on non-forested lands countrywide.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] These plantations were used to analyze how afforestation can help to increase carbon sequestration and mitigate greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions while also considering the economic and investment attractiveness of afforestation.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] On 14 December 2020, Canada's Minister of Natural Resources Seamus O'Regan announced the federal government's investment of $3.16 billion to plant two billion trees over the next 10 years.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This plan aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by an estimated 12 megatonnes by 2050.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] China had the highest afforestation rate of any country or region in the world, with 4.77 million hectares (47,000 square kilometers) of afforestation in 2008.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] According to the 2021 government work report, forest coverage will reach 24 percent based on the main targets and tasks for the 14th Five-Year Plan period.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] A law in China from 1981 requires that every school student over the age of 11 plants at least one tree per year.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] From 2011 to 2016, the city Dongying in Shandong province forested over 13,800 hectares of saline soil through the Shandong Ecological Afforestation Project, which was launched with support from the World Bank.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In 2017, the Saihanba Afforestation Community won the UN Champions of the Earth Award in the Inspiration and Action category for "transforming degraded land into a lush paradise".
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The successful afforestation of the Loess Plateau involved collaborative efforts by international and domestic professionals alongside villagers.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Through this initiative, millions of villagers across four of China's poorest provinces were able to improve farming practices and increase incomes and employment, alleviating poverty.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In addition, the careful selection of trees ensured a healthy, self-sustainable ecosystem between tree and soil which facilitated a net carbon sink.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The Loess Plateau, although successful, was costly, reaching almost US$500 million.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This contrasts with more recent initiatives where the results have not been as favorable.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In an attempt to make afforestation both low-cost and less time-consuming, China shifted towards monoculture of mostly red pine trees.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] However, this did not adequately take into consideration environmental structure and led to increased soil erosion, desertification, sand/dust storms and short-lived trees.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This has reduced China's environmental sustainability index (ESI) to one of the lowest in the world.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Regarding the effects of afforestation on long-term carbon stocks and carbon sequestration these decrease when trees are less than 5 years old and increase quickly thereafter.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This means trees from monoculture planting that do not survive never reach full potential for carbon sequestration to offset China's carbon output.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Overall, there is a possibility for afforestation to balance carbon levels and aid carbon neutrality, but several challenges still remain which hinder an all encompassing effort.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The Chinese government requires mining companies to restore the environment around exhausted mines by refilling excavated pits and planting crops or trees.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Many mining companies use these recovered mines for ecotourism business.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Europe deforested more than half of its forested areas over the last 6000 years.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The European Union (EU) has paid farmers for afforestation since 1990, offering grants to turn farmland into forest and payments for the management of forest.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] As part of the Green Deal, the EU program "3 Billion Tree Planting Pledge by 2030" provides direction on afforestation of previous farmland in addition to reforestation.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] According to Food and Agriculture Organization statistics, Spain had the third fastest afforestation rate in Europe in the 1990–2005 period, after Iceland and Ireland.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In those years, a total of 44,360 square kilometers were afforested, and the total forest cover rose from 13.5 to 17.9 million hectares.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In 1990, forests covered 26.6% of the Spanish territory.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] As of 2007, that figure had risen to 36.6%.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Spain today has the fifth largest forest area in the European Union.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] As of 2023 the total forest and tree cover in India was 22%.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The forests of India are grouped into 5 major categories and 16 types based on biophysical criteria.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] 38% of the forest is categorized as subtropical dry deciduous and 30% as tropical moist deciduous and other smaller groups.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In 2016 the Indian government passed the CAMPA (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management and Planning Authority) law, allowing about 40 thousand crores rupees (almost $6 Billion) to go to Indian states for planting trees.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In 2016 the Maharashtra government planted almost 20,000,000 saplings and pledged to plant another 30,000,000 the following year.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In 2019, 220 million trees were planted in a single day in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] With wood production as a main objective, monocultures of Aleppo pine were vigorously planted between 1948 and the 1970s.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Following a massive collapse of this species in the 1990s, due to attacks by the insect pine blast scale, the Aleppo pine was gradually replaced by Pinus brutia.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Since the 1990s there has been a trend towards more ecological approaches planting mixed forests combining pines with broadleaf Mediterranean species e.g. oak, pistachio, carob, olive, arbutus and buckthorn.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] About 250 million trees have been planted through the JNF across Israel since 1990.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Tree coverage increased from 2% in 1948 to over 8% at present.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The Japanese temperate rainforest is well sustained and maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] One method that has been utilized in maintaining the health of forests in Japan has been afforestation.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The Japanese government and private businesses have set up multiple projects to plant native tree species in open areas scattered throughout the country.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] This practice has resulted in shifts in forest structure and a healthy temperate rainforest that maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In January 2013, the UK government set a target of 12% woodland cover in England by 2060, up from the then 10%.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In Wales the National Assembly for Wales has set a target of 19% woodland cover, up from 15%.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Government-backed initiatives such as the Woodland Carbon Code are intended to support this objective by encouraging corporations and landowners to create new woodland to offset their carbon emissions.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Charitable groups such as Trees for Life (Scotland) contribute to afforestation and reforestation efforts in the UK.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Afforestation efforts in Scotland have provided an increase in woodland expansion.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] By the 20th century mark, Scotland had diminished woodland coverage to 5% of Scotland's land area.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] However, by the early 21st century, afforestation efforts have increased woodland coverage to 17%.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The Scottish government released their Draft Climate Change Plan in January 2017.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] The 2017 draft plan has increased the targeted woodland coverage to 21% by 2032 and increases the afforestation rate to 15,000 hectares per year.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] In the 1800s people moving westward in the US encountered the Great Plains – land with fertile soil, a growing population and a demand for timber but with few trees to supply it.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] So tree planting was encouraged along homesteads.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Arbor Day was founded in 1872 by Julius Sterling Morton in Nebraska City.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] By the 1930s the Dust Bowl environmental disaster signified a reason for adding significant new tree cover.
[src:bird-conservation/afforestation] Public works programs under the New Deal saw the planting of 18,000 miles of windbreaks stretching from North Dakota to Texas to fight soil erosion (see Great Plains Shelterbelt).
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:bird-conservation/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] See Late Quaternary prehistoric birds for birds which disappeared in prehistoric and early historic times, usually due to human activity (i.e., starting with the Upper Paleolithic Revolution).
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] For birds having gone extinct in modern times (since 1500), see List of extinct birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Since the Late Pleistocene period, it is estimated that 1,430 (95% credible interval: 1327–1544) bird extinctions have occurred.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Human activity has been directly attributed to almost all bird species extinctions, specifically prehistoric and early historical species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] During the Upper Paleolithic period, human societies began spreading across the globe, leading to the overhunting of species and the introduction of invasive species to new environments.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] A particularly significant period of extinction occurred when humans colonized the islands of Melanesia, Polynesia, and Micronesia around 4,000 years ago.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] According to a study published in *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, early Polynesian settlers are often credited with contributing to the extinction of over 1,000 bird species during this time, majority of which were non-passerine land birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Before the Industrial Revolution (1750-1850), most bird species were not yet heavily impacted by habitat loss or climate change.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] However, overexploitation through hunting, bird collecting, as well as the introduction of invasive species became significant threats.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Industrialization marked a turning point in the relationship between humans and birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The technological growth, urban expansion, and increased emissions from industrial activity caused widespread habitat destruction and altered ecosystems.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] In the United Kingdom, species such as the white-tailed eagle (*Haliaeetus albicilla*) and cranes, for example, were recognized as more abundant before industrialization began.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] By the 19th century, the advent of industrial-scale hunting and urban sprawl had put pressure on many bird populations.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The species' final extinction came in the early 20th century, though causes remain unclear.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Similarly, the passenger pigeon (*Ectopistes migratorius*) once one of the most populous bird species in North America, was driven to extinction in the early 20th century due to relentless hunting and habitat loss.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] This extinction served as a stark reminder of the fragility of bird populations in the face of human intervention.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The loss of such a previously abundant species helped catalyze the first major bird conservation efforts in the United States.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Following the assumed extinction of passenger pigeons, Theodore Roosevelt claimed to have witnessed a small flock of the birds at his family name’s rural cabin in Virginia some 25 years after their extinction (March 24, 1900).
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Following this sighting, Theodore recognized the severity of the loss of this once abundant species and initiated strengthened bird advocacy legislation during his presidency in 1907.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The establishment of the first Federal Bird Reserve on Pelican Island in Florida can be attributed to this sighting made by President Roosevelt.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The early 20th century saw the rise of formal conservation efforts.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The National Audubon Society, founded in 1905, played a key role in raising awareness about the rapid decline of bird populations, specifically in response to the exploitation of birds for the feather trade.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The organization's efforts were influential in propelling early legal protections for birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] A significant achievement in favor of bird protection was the passage of the Migratory Bird Treaty Act of 1918.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] This act provided international protection for migratory bird species between the United States, Canada, Mexico, Japan, and Russia.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] From the 1920s to 1950s, bird advocacy gained further strength.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] It sought to fund the protection of wetlands using hunter fees.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Additionally, during the Great Depression, New Deal programs including the Civilian Conservation Corps preserved wildlife refuges, providing birds a thriving environment for bird species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Birdwatching gained popularity within this timeframe, too, in large part thanks to Roger Tory Peterson’s groundbreaking field guides.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Finally, Rachel Carson's early works began to clarify the relationship between healthy bird populations and a healthy planet.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] All of these factors laid more solid groundwork for the continuation of advocacy for birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The 1960s were a particularly pivotal era in favor of bird conservation.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The publication of Rachel Carson’s *Silent Spring* (1962) aided in exposing widespread dangers of pesticide use, particularly DDT, on bird populations.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Her groundbreaking work demonstrated how DDT led to the thinning of eggshells in species like the bald eagle (*Haliaeetus leucocephalus*) and peregrine falcon (*Falco peregrinus*), resulting in reproductive failures.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Carson’s book ignited a broader environmental movement, leading to significant policy changes, and the eventual DDT ban.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The Environmental Protection Agency enforced a generalized ban on DDT pesticides in 1972.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Bald eagles made a famous comeback during the “dirty sixties” thanks to this ban, along with the brown pelican (*Pelecanus occidentalis*) and peregrine falcon.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] By the 1980s, the global conservation movement gained further momentum.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Organizations like BirdLife International played an increasingly vital role in establishing international frameworks for bird protection.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] This included efforts to protect critical habitats, such as wetland areas, and to monitor at-risk species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Additionally, the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) developed the Red List of Threatened Species, which continues to serve as an important tool for identifying and tracking species at risk of extinction, including many bird species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The most critical threat facing threatened birds is the destruction and fragmentation of habitat.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The loss of forests, plains and other natural systems into agriculture, mines, and urban developments, the draining of swamps and other wetlands, and logging reduce potential habitat for many species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] In addition the remaining patches of habitat are often too small or fragmented by the construction of roads or other such barriers that cause populations in these fragmented *islands* to become vulnerable to localized extinction.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] In addition many forest species show limited abilities to disperse and occupy new forest fragments (see island biogeography).
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The loss of tropical rainforest is the most pressing problem, as these forests hold the highest number of species yet are being destroyed quickly.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Habitat loss has been implicated in a number of extinctions, including the ivory-billed woodpecker (*Campephilus principalis*) (disputed because of "rediscovery"), Bachman's warbler (*Vermivora bachmanii*), and the dusky seaside sparrow (*Ammospiza maritima nigrescens*).
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Climate change is a catalyst for the worrying downward trend of bird populations globally.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The speed of human-caused climate change is currently unprecedented, leading bird species into continuously unadaptable circumstances.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] It has been observed that most North American bird species have been recognized over the prior few decades to have shifted their breeding ranges irregularly due to climate change.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Migratory birds are more prone to the effects of climate change, leading to shifts in time migratory patterns.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] It is predicted in the coming years that mountainous birds will even lose suitable migratory habitats due to rising temperatures at higher elevations.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] On top of these migratory shifts, global warming has been predicted to be changing size and wing length proportionally in all bird species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] It is presumed that with rising temperatures, smaller birds maintain better competitive fitness thanks to their easier heat dispersal compared to their larger counterparts within the same species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Indirect impacts of climate change on birds include increased drought and fires, rising-sea levels, increased disease, phenological mismatch, and uncommon interactions between species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Increase in drought leads to increased fires, destroying nesting ground and fragmenting specifically sagebrush ecosystems.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Rise in sea-levels provides similar altercations for marsh-nesting birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Nesting sites disappear as sea-levels rise, eliminating habitats for nesting parents and young to continue species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Phenological mismatch occurs due to rising temperatures shifting migratory timeframes but not quickly enough, altering the life cycle events in interacting species at different rates.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Birds are afflicted by numerous pollutants including marine oil pollution, plastic pollution, light pollution, sound pollution, air pollution, and pesticides to name a major few.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Plastic pollution serves a major detriment to birds, mainly marine birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Many marine birds suffer from entanglement, nutritional deprivation, and gut damage due to ingested plastic litter.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Historically the threat posed by introduced species has probably caused the most extinctions of birds, particularly on islands. most prehistoric human caused extinctions were insular as well.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Many island species evolved in the absence of predators and consequently lost many anti-predator behaviors.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] As humans traveled around the world they brought with them many foreign animals which disturbed these island species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Some of these were unfamiliar predators, like rats, feral cats, and pigs; others were competitors, such as other bird species, or herbivores that degraded breeding habitat.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Disease can also play a role; introduced avian malaria is thought to be a primary cause of many extinctions in Hawaii.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Many species currently threatened with extinction are vulnerable to introduced species, such as the kōkako (*Callaeas* species), black robin *(Petroica traversi)*, Mariana crow (*Corvus kubaryi*), and the Hawaiian duck (*Anas wyvilliana*).
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Humans have exploited birds for a very long time, and sometimes this exploitation has resulted in extinction.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Overhunting occurred in some instances with a naive species unfamiliar with humans, such as the moa of New Zealand, in other cases it was an industrial level of hunting that led to extinction.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The passenger pigeon was once the most numerous species of bird alive (possibly ever), overhunting reduced a species that once numbered in the billions to extinction.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Hunting pressure can be for food, sport, feathers, or even come from scientists collecting museum specimens.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Collection of great auks for museums pushed the already rare species to extinction.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The harvesting of parrots for the pet trade has led to many species becoming endangered.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Between 1986 and 1988, two million parrots were legally imported into the US alone.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Parrots are also illegally smuggled between countries, and rarer species can command high prices.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Organized entrapment of birds takes place today across the globe, specifically in Latin America, Asia, and Africa.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The demand for exotic pet birds in the United States drives capture in Bolivia and Mexico, with a supposed over 22,000 individuals of 31 parrot species illegally traded under Bolivian law every year and an estimated 65,000–78,500 parrots captured every year in Mexico.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] This poaching continues due to the potential profits, with rarer species selling for up to $1,000 each when caught illegally.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Plume hunting is the hunting of wild birds to harvest their decorative feathers.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] More decorative plumes, which were sold for use as ornamentation particularly in hat-making, were more sought after in the trade.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] While the plume trade is not necessarily a large ongoing threat to birds, it was in its height in the late 19th century into the early 20th century until protective efforts were instated.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Hybridization may also endanger birds, damaging the gene stock.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] For example, the American black duck (*Anas rubripes*) has been often reported hybridizing with the mallard (*Anas platyrhynchos*), starting a slow decline in the rarer *A. rubripes*.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Gamebird hybrids are particularly common and many breeders produce hybrids that may be accidentally or intentionally introduced into the wild.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Pollution has led to serious declines in some species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Increasingly large volumes of plastic waste are being transported by wind and ocean currents throughout the planet, and mistaken ingestion by many species is eventually fatal.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Seabirds are also vulnerable to oil spills, which destroy the plumage's waterproofing, causing the birds to drown or die of hypothermia.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Light pollution can also have a damaging effect on some species, particularly nocturnal seabirds such as petrels.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The pesticide DDT was responsible for thinning egg shells in nesting birds, particularly seabirds and birds of prey that are high on the food chain.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The use of pesticides continues to harm birds, especially insectivores like swallows that have lost a food source from the use of insecticides in agriculture.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] A particularly dangerous class of pesticides is the seed-coating neonicotinoids.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Neonicotinoids include a neurotoxin that bioaccumulates in the tissue of birds and is associated with impairment of reproduction.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Seabirds face another threat in the form of bycatch, where birds in the water become tangled in fishing nets or hooked on lines set out by long-line fisheries.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] As many as 100,000 albatrosses are hooked and drown each year on tuna lines set out by long-line fisheries.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Birds are also threatened by high rise buildings, communications towers, and other human-related activities and structures; estimates vary from about 3.5 to 975 million birds a year in the North America alone.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The largest source of human-related bird death is due to glass windows, which kill 100–900 million birds a year.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The next largest sources of human-caused death are hunting (100+ million), house cats (100 million), cars and trucks (50 to 100 million), electric power lines (174 million), and pesticides (67 million).
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Birds are also killed in large quantities by flying into communication tower guidelines, usually after being attracted by tower lights.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] This phenomenon is called towerkill and is responsible for 5–50 million birds deaths a year.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Similarly, natural gas flaring can attract and kill large numbers of birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Approximately 7,500 migrating songbirds were attracted to and killed by the flare at the liquefied natural gas terminal in Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada, on September 13, 2013.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Similar incidents have occurred at flares on offshore oil and gas installations.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The recent growth in the renewable energy industry is also increasing the threat to birds farther away from dense human population centers.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] As of late 2019, the capacity of wind power in the U.S. reached 100 GW (gigawatt).
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Studies conducted at a variety of farms found fewer than 14, and typically fewer than 4, direct bird deaths per year per installed megawatt; suggesting cumulative mortality is approaching the order of a million individuals annually.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Migrating songbirds appeared to be the most strongly impacted in some studies.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The primary impact of commercial solar farms – the majority utilizing photovoltaic collectors which are mounted near the ground – is from extensive land clearing and increases in long-distance power transmission infrastructure.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] According to a 2018 *Nature* paper studying trends in global waterbird populations, ineffective governance is a major driver of biodiversity loss in wetlands, highlighting the importance of political and institutional factors in conservation outcomes.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Scientists and conservation professionals have developed a number of techniques to protect bird species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] These techniques have had varying levels of success.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Captive breeding, or *ex-situ* conservation, has been used in a number of instances to save species from extinction.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The principle is to create a viable population of a species in either zoos or breeding facilities, for later reintroduction back into the wild.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] A captive population can either serve as an insurance against the species going extinct in the wild or as a last-ditch effort in situations where conservation in the wild is impossible.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Captive breeding has been used to save several species from extinction, the most famous example being the California condor, a species that declined to less than thirty birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] In order to save the California condor the decision was made to take every individual left in the wild into captivity.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] From these 22 individuals a breeding program began that brought the numbers up to 273 by 2005.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] An even more impressive recovery was that of the Mauritius kestrel (*Falco punctatus*), which by 1974 had dropped to only four individuals, yet by 2006 the population increased to 800.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Reintroductions of captive bred populations can occur to replenish wild populations of an endangered species, to create new populations or to restore a species after it has become extinct in the wild.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Reintroductions helped bring the wild populations of Hawaiian geese (nene) (*Branta sandvicensis)* from 30 birds to over 500.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The Mauritius kestrel was successfully reintroduced into the wild after its captive breeding programme.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Reintroductions can be very difficult and often fail if insufficient preparations are made, as species born in captivity may lack the skills and knowledge needed for life in the wild after living in captivity.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Reintroductions can also fail if the causes of a birds decline have not been adequately addressed.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Attempts to reintroduce the Bali starling (*Leucopsar rothschildi*) into the wild failed due to continued poaching of reintroduced birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The introduction of captives of unknown pedigree can also pose a threat to native populations.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Domestic fowl have threatened endemic species such as *Gallus g. bankiva* while pheasants such as the ring-necked pheasant (*Phasianus colchicus*) and captive cheer pheasants (*Catreus wallichii*) of uncertain origin have escaped into the wild or have been intentionally introduced.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Green peafowl (*Pavo muticus*) of similar mixed origins confiscated from local bird dealers have been released into areas with native wild birds.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Translocations involve moving populations of threatened species into areas of suitable habitat currently unused by the species.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] There are several reasons for doing this; the creation of secondary populations that act as an insurance against disaster, or in many cases threats faced by the original population in its current location.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] One famous translocation was of the kākāpō (*Strigops habroptilus*) of New Zealand.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] These large flightless parrots were unable to cope with introduced predators in their remaining habitat on Stewart Island, so were moved to smaller offshore islands that had been cleared of predators.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] From there a recovery program has managed to maintain and eventually increase their numbers.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] As the loss and destruction of habitat is the most serious threat facing many bird species, conservation organizations and government agencies tasked with protecting birds work to protect areas of natural habitat.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] This can be achieved through purchasing land of conservation importance, setting aside land or gazetting it as a national park or other protected area, and passing legislation preventing landowners from undertaking damaging land use practices, or paying them not to undertake those activities.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] The goals of habitat protection for birds and other threatened animals and plants often conflicts with other stakeholders, such as landowners and businesses, who can face economically damaging restrictions on their activities.
[src:bird-conservation/bird-conservation] Plans to protect crucial habitat for the spotted owl (*Strix occidentalis*) of North America required the protection of large areas of old growth forest in the western United States; this was opposed by logging companies who claimed it would cause job losses and reduced profits.
